trust automatically.\\\"\\n\\nYou can configure trusted commands at:\\n- **User level** (global across all workspaces)\\n- **Workspace level** (specific to your current project)\\n\\nAccess via: `Settings → Kiro Agent: Trusted Commands`\\n\\n## How Auto-Approval Works\\n\\nTrusted commands use **prefix matching** to auto-approve commands starting with specific patterns. Three matching types exist:\\n\\n1. **Exact matching**: `[\\\"npm install\\\"]` approves only that exact command\\n2. **Partial wildcard**: `[\\\"npm install *\\\"]` approves variations like `npm install --save`\\n3. **Full wildcard**: `[\\\"npm *\\\"]` approves any command starting with `npm `\\n\\n## Command Denylist Setting\\n\\nThe `kiroAgent.commandDenylist` provides an override layer using **substring matching**. If any denied pattern appears anywhere in a command, it requires manual approval regardless of trust settings.\\n\\nConfigure via: `Settings → Kiro Agent: Command Denylist`\\n\\nRecommended patterns to block: `rm -rf`, `sudo`, `chmod 777`, `eval`, `curl | sh`, `wget | sh`, `> /dev/`, `mkfs`, `dd if=`\\n\\n## Evaluation Order\\n\\nCommands are processed as: **Denylist (highest priority) → Trust check → Default (requires approval)**\"}]},\"uuid\":\"74b1198a-8095-48b2-8f00-209a099b40f5\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-03T21:19:05.326Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"bytes\":189953,\"code\":200,\"codeText\":\"OK\",\"result\":\"# Kiro Terminal Command Approval System\\n\\nKiro uses a **two-layer security approach** for terminal command management:\\n\\n## Trust Commands Setting\\n\\nYes, there is a `kiroAgent.trustedCommands` setting. According to the documentation, this allows you to \\\"streamline the approval process by configuring which commands to trust automatically.\\\"\\n\\nYou can configure trusted commands at:\\n- **User level** (global across all workspaces)\\n- **Workspace level** (specific to your current project)\\n\\nAccess via: `Settings → Kiro Agent: Trusted Commands`\\n\\n## How Auto-Approval Works\\n\\nTrusted commands use **prefix matching** to auto-approve commands starting with specific patterns. Three matching types exist:\\n\\n1. **Exact matching**: `[\\\"npm install\\\"]` approves only that exact command\\n2. **Partial wildcard**: `[\\\"npm install *\\\"]` approves variations like `npm install --save`\\n3. **Full wildcard**: `[\\\"npm *\\\"]` approves any command starting with `npm `\\n\\n## Command Denylist Setting\\n\\nThe `kiroAgent.commandDenylist` provides an override layer using **substring matching**. If any denied pattern appears anywhere in a command, it requires manual approval regardless of trust settings.\\n\\nConfigure via: `Settings → Kiro Agent: Command Denylist`\\n\\nRecommended patterns to block: `rm -rf`, `sudo`, `chmod 777`, `eval`, `curl | sh`, `wget | sh`, `> /dev/`, `mkfs`, `dd if=`\\n\\n## Evaluation Order\\n\\nCommands are processed as: **Denylist (highest priority) → Trust check → Default (requires approval)**\",\"durationMs\":6438,\"url\":\"https://kiro.dev/docs/chat/terminal/\"},\"sourceToolAssistantUUID\":\"939800ab-4bf4-4f1b-8fe2-c659d1fc56d4\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"74b1198a-8095-48b2-8f00-209a099b40f5\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot\",\"sessionId\":\"4ab3ddd7-2bb2-4d33-bbe6-7ee25ce1f55e\",\"version\":\"2.1.63\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/kiro-oneshot\",\"slug\":\"glittery-waddling-parrot\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01CbVjPL6W6GUpjn29Bcn5ad\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"Now I understand the issue. The Kiro IDE has a `kiroAgent.trustedCommands` setting that controls which terminal commands are auto-approved. Our hooks run shell commands like `entire hooks kiro user-prompt-submit`, and by default these require approval because they're not in the trusted commands list.\\n\\nThe fix should be to configure the `kiroAgent.trustedCommands` setting to include `entire